1.	Give an example of synchronous communication in telecommunication networks.
Synchronous communication means sender and receiver communicate at the same time and stay synchronized with a clock or timing signal. 

Example; Telephone call, Video call, Real-time voice communication
Both sides send and receive data continuously and simultaneously.

2.	In a layered communication protocol, the lower layer adds information (e.g. addresses, check sums) to the data provided by the higher layer. Is this statement true or is it the other way round? Give a reason for your answer.
In a layered model like OSI, each layer performs a process called Encapsulation. When data moves from a higher layer to a lower layer treats the entire higher-layer packet as ‘data’ and wraps it owns information around it.
-	Headers: Added to the front (e.g., IP addresses at the Network layer)
-	Trailers: Added to the end (e.g., Checksums at the Data Link layer to detect errors)


1. THE CORE THEORY (The "Must-Know" Concepts)
A. The OSI Model & Data Encapsulation
The exam focuses on how data changes as it moves through layers.
•	Encapsulation (Sending): Higher layers pass data to lower layers. Each lower layer adds a Header (Control info). The Data Link layer also adds a Trailer (Error checking).
•	Decapsulation (Receiving): The process is reversed. Each layer strips off its header.
•	Data Units (PDUs):
o	Transport: Segment
o	Network: Packet
o	Data Link: Frame
o	Physical: Bits
B. Hardware: Routers vs. Switches
•	Switch (Layer 2): Connects devices on the same local network (LAN). It uses MAC Addresses and a "MAC Table."
•	Router (Layer 3): Connects different networks. It uses IP Addresses and a "Routing Table."
C. Protocols: TCP vs. UDP
•	TCP (Transmission Control Protocol): Connection-oriented. Uses a 3-way handshake. Reliable (retransmits lost data). Used for Web, Email.
•	UDP (User Datagram Protocol): Connectionless. Fast. No retransmission. Used for VoIP, Streaming, Gaming.
D. Transmission & Synchronization
•	Synchronous: Sender and Receiver share a Common Clock. Very fast, constant stream.
•	Asynchronous: No shared clock. Uses Start/Stop bits to tell the receiver when data starts/ends.
