2. EXAM QUESTION BANK (10 Essential Patterns)
Q1: What is the main purpose of the Trailer in a Data Link Frame?
•	Answer: To provide a Checksum (CRC) for error detection. If the bits change during transmission, the trailer allows the receiver to detect the corruption.
Q2: Which layer is responsible for end-to-end flow control and error recovery?
•	Answer: Layer 4 (Transport Layer), specifically using the TCP protocol.
Q3: Is an IP address permanent?
•	Answer: No. An IP address is Logical and can change. The MAC Address is the physical, permanent address of the hardware.
Q4: What happens if a router receives a packet with an unknown destination IP?
•	Answer: It checks its Routing Table. If no route exists, it sends the packet to its "Default Gateway" or drops it.
Q5: Why is Synchronous transmission more efficient for large files?
•	Answer: It has less overhead. It doesn't need to add start/stop bits to every byte, saving bandwidth for actual data.
Q6: Trace the path: A packet moves from the Network Layer to the Data Link Layer. What is added?
•	Answer: A MAC Header (source/destination MAC) and a Trailer (CRC).
Q7: Which device reduces "Collision Domains" by using MAC addresses?
•	Answer: A Switch. (Unlike a Hub, which broadcasts to everyone).
Q8: What are the three steps of the TCP Handshake?
•	Answer: SYN -> SYN-ACK -> ACK.
Q9: Does the Physical Layer understand IP addresses?
•	Answer: No. The Physical Layer only understands Bits (electrical signals, light pulses, or radio waves).
Q10: What is the difference between a Packet and a Frame?
•	Answer: A Packet is the data unit at the Network Layer (contains IP). A Frame is that packet encapsulated at the Data Link Layer (contains MAC).


